authSocket PACKAGE

The authSocket package contains two important Component classes
responsible for configuring user identity verification and proactively
managing user connection sessions. Specifically:

    1.  WsAuthInterceptor Component
        This is a Component class responsible for identifying users who access
        the WebSocket through a specific user token.

        This Component class is initialized because the Spring Frontend
        application located in the admin [FE_Admin] directory acts as a
        Proxy BFF (Backend For Frontend) and does not directly manage users
        via HttpSession like the core backend server.

        Therefore, when a user connects to the WebSocket, the BFF cannot
        automatically recognize the identity of that user.

        The WsAuthInterceptor Component class helps the BFF perform user
        identification when the user successfully logs in, where the token
        is the required data used to authenticate that user.

        The logic can be reviewed at:
            admin/src/main/resources/static/assets/js/app/main.js

    2.  WebSocketEventListener Component
        This is a Component class responsible for managing WebSocket connection
        sessions for both the CONNECT and DISCONNECT states, without relying
        on direct user actions.

        In the case of a successful login, the socket automatically recognizes
        that the user has connected to the WebSocket.

        In the DISCONNECT state (when the token expires and the session ends,
        or when the user performs a logout), the socket automatically detects
        the event and sends a notification through the downstream channel of
        the WebSocket to the UI that has subscribed to these notifications.

Conclusion
Therefore, in the case where my Spring Frontend admin application acts
as a BFF, these two Component classes are essential when using the
WebSocket service without depending on the core backend of the entire
project, which is the server [dabble].

These two Component classes are applied to users who access the application directly through the admin BFF.
For users accessing from another application, the WebsocketController is responsible for receiving and
recording the data.